1. Introduction¶

This project is an Explorative and Explanative analysis of a Loan data set provided by Udacity. The dataset for this project consists of 113,937 loan records with 81 variables. Some of the key variables include Loan Amount, Borrower Income, and Loan Term amongst many others.

To understand the complete variables, here is the data dictionary

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset I would be working with consists of 113,937 loan records with 81 variables.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main feature(s) of interest for me are insights related to the borrower, i.e, LoanOriginalAmount.  I would explore the features associated with Loan Original Amount, its relationship with other variables, and how their correlation is affected by another variable.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

In order to understand and investigate the main feature(s) of interest, I would be looking at the following features or variables:

  • MemberKey:The unique key that is associated with the borrower. This is the same identifier that is used in the API member object.
  • EmploymentStatus:The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.
  • Occupation:The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.
  • StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  • IncomeRange: The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.
  • BorrowerRate:The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
  • BorrowerState: The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created.
  • IsBorrowerHomeowner: A Borrower will be classified as a homowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.
  • CreditScoreRangeLower: The lower value representing the range of the borrower's credit score as provided by a consumer credit rating agency.
  • CreditScoreRangeUpper: The upper value representing the range of the borrower's credit score as provided by a consumer credit rating agency.
  • LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.
  • Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  • LoanOriginationDate: The date the loan was originated.
  • MonthlyLoanPayment: The scheduled monthly loan payment.
  • EmploymentStatusDuration: The length in months of the employment status at the time the listing was created.
  • ProsperScore: A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.

3. Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, the distribution of individual variables would be investigated.

In [13]:
#Converting IncomeRange into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dict = {'IncomeRange' : ['Not displayed', 'Not employed', '$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999',
                                   '$75,000-99,999','$100,000+']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    loan_subset[var] = loan_subset[var].astype(ordered_var)
In [14]:
#Creating a custom Python function for label to avoid repetitive coding. 
def label(x, y, z):
    """
    Args:
    x(str): x-axis title
    y(str): y-axis title
    z(str): main title
    
    Returns:
    None
    """
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y)
    plt.title(z)
    plt.show()

def loan_month_plot():
    #Convert LoanOriginationDate to Datetime
    loan_subset['LoanOriginationDate'] = pd.to_datetime(loan_subset.LoanOriginationDate)
    #Extracting month from the 'LoanOriginationDate' variable
    loan_subset['Month'] = loan_subset['LoanOriginationDate'].dt.month
    #Plotting
    plt.figure(figsize = [8, 5])
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.countplot(data = loan_subset, x = 'Month', color = base_color)
    label('Month', 'Frequency', 'Month Distribution');

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

My variable of interest was LoanOriginalAmount. The majority of the borrowers took loans between 5k - 15k, and only a small number of them earned between 5k - 7500k. Comparing these two scenarios made me realize why the majority of the loan duration was 36 months. The amount borrowed almost doubles their salary, therefore they would need a more flexible and long-term plan to pay back the loan.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I had to extract the year and month the loan was given from the LoanOriginationDate variable in order to know the year and month that had the highest number of borrowers.

The occupation of the highest number of borrowers that accessed the loan seemed odd to me. Because pretty much almost every profession was covered by the various designation. My deduction is that the 'Other' could be jobless or doing nothing significant.

Interestingly, those with a higher IncomeRange between 75k - 100+k can access a higher amount of loan compared to those with a lower IncomeRange. The occupation with the highest access to loan amounts is Judges, followed closely by Pharmacists and Doctors.

Most 'Employed' borrowers own their homes while the borrowers with the highest IncomeRange of 100k+ also own their homes.

6. Conclusion¶

The dataset for this analysis was directly downloaded into Pandas dataframe, and afterward, it was assessed. I had to pick a few variables of interest to investigate because the number of variables was much. Having made a subset of the variables I was interested in, I started investigating the variables by doing a univariate exploration.

In the univariate exploration, I investigated individual variables using appropriate plots or visualization to see their distribution. Original Loan Amount was my main feature, and it was interesting to note that the majority of the borrowers had their work designation as 'Other', and the monthly income for the majority of the borrowers ranges between 5k - 7500k. The Term, i.e loan duration for most of the borrowers was 36 months. A large chunk of the loan was accessed in 2013 around January and December.

Doing a bivariate analysis or exploration also threw up a few insights. The borrowers that accessed higher loans were found to have a higher IncomeRange ranging between 75k - 100K+, and there is a positive correlation between the loan amount accessed and payment.

The multivariate exploration basically reinforces the relationships and insights already generated. However, worthy of note is the equal number of borrowers with homes and those without homes accessing the same loan amount.

Note: One of the challenges encountered was having to choose which features to focus on because there were too many variables to choose from. I also heavily relied on the codes from Udacity classroom and a few from Google for this project.
